com.amoerie.jstreams

Class Stream<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.amoerie.jstreams.Stream<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of each element in the stream
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Group

    public abstract class Stream<E>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<E>
    Represents a collection of elements that are not known at construction time This is a wrapper around the Iterator class, providing more functional methods than is standard provided by Java, by combining some classic functional paradigms such as map and flatMap.

      • reduce

        public <R> R reduce(Reducer<E,R> reducer,
                    R initialValue)
        Reduces this stream to a single value by repeatedly applying the same reduction operator to the current value and the next element. For example, to reduce a stream of integers to a sum: 
          int sum = numbers.reduce(new Reducer<Integer, Integer>() {
          public Integer reduce(Integer sum, Integer number) {
              return sum + number;
          }
     }, 0)
        Type Parameters:
        R - the type of the result of the reduced stream
        Parameters:
        reducer - the reduction function that turns the current value and the next element into the next value
        initialValue - the initial value to start from. This is also the value that will be returned when the stream is empty.
        Returns:
        the final value after reducing every element

      • sort

        public Stream<E> sort(java.util.Comparator<E> comparator)
        Sorts this stream using the provided comparator. This operator is lazy but greedy, meaning that it will wait as long as possible to actually materialize your stream to sort it. Once you start iterating over the elements, it will sort just in time. Note that multiple iterations will also a separate sort every time.
        Parameters:
        comparator - the comparator to use as the basis for the sorting
        Returns:
        a new stream containing all elements of this stream in the order as specified by the comparator

      • toMap

        public <K> java.util.Map<K,E> toMap(Mapper<E,K> keyMapper)
        Creates a Map from this stream. Note that the map will only contain one element for each key. If two elements with the same key are encountered, only the last one is retained. If you expect there to be scenarios where a key can be present multiple times, use groupBy(Mapper) instead.
        Type Parameters:
        K - the type of the key for each entry in the map
        Parameters:
        keyMapper - the mapper function that computes a key for each element
        Returns:
        a new map containing entries for each element (that had a unique key)

        Creates a Map from this stream. Note that the map will only contain one element for each key. If two elements with the same key are encountered, only the last one is retained. If you expect there to be scenarios where a key can be present multiple times, use groupBy(Mapper) instead.
        Type Parameters:

        V - the type of the value for each entry in the map

        public Stream<E> without(Stream<E> other)
        Filters out elements from this stream based on the elements from another. Only elements that are NOT in the other stream are allowed to pass through.
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        a new stream containing only elements that cannot be found in the other stream
